{
    "analysis": "None",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv, and error_logs.csv. For each file do the following and return results as compact tables (limit any listing to top 20 items):\n1) Report the total row count and the min(timestamp) and max(timestamp).\n2) Report the top 20 unique cmdb_id values and their row counts (sorted by count desc).\n3) For metric.csv: list all unique kpi_name values and their counts (top 20). For trace.csv: list all unique trace_name values and their counts (top 20). For log.csv: list all unique log_name values and their counts (top 20). For error_logs.csv: show top 20 distinct messages and their counts.\nReturn results only (no plots). Keep outputs compact."
}

{
    "analysis": "The previous step loaded and summarized all telemetry files. We have full-file counts and timestamp ranges: metric.csv covers 07:30–08:30 (UTC+8) with many component-KPI combinations; trace.csv and log.csv cover the incident window; error_logs.csv is empty. This discovery confirms metric.csv contains wide KPI coverage including many container and node KPIs and will be the best first source to find anomalies. Next we should run metric-based preprocessing and anomaly detection (global thresholds computed on full series then inspect 08:00–08:30) to narrow down candidate faulty component-KPIs.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv only, do the following and return compact tabular results (limit rows to top 20):\n1) For each unique (cmdb_id, kpi_name) compute global statistics over the full file: count_all, min, max, p50, p90, p95, p99. Count how many distinct (cmdb_id,kpi_name) series exist.\n2) Filter metric.csv to the incident window: March 21, 2022 08:00 to 08:30 (Asia/Shanghai) inclusive. For each (cmdb_id,kpi_name) present in that window compute: count_in_window, anomalies_count = number of points with value > p95 (use the p95 computed over the full series), earliest_anomaly_timestamp (smallest timestamp where value>p95), max_value_in_window, p95_value (from step 1), and percent_exceedance = 100*(max_value_in_window - p95_value)/p95_value (if p95_value==0, set percent_exceedance to NULL or 'inf').\n3) Return: total number of (cmdb_id,kpi_name) series scanned, and a table of top 20 rows sorted by anomalies_count desc, then percent_exceedance desc, showing columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, count_all, count_in_window, anomalies_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, p95_value, max_value_in_window, percent_exceedance.\nKeep outputs compact, do not print full raw time series. If no anomalies are found using p95, also compute anomalies using p90 and include a small note (boolean) per series whether anomalies were found at p90 when none at p95."
}

{
    "analysis": "Previous step computed global pXX thresholds per (cmdb_id, kpi_name) and then inspected the incident window (2022-03-21 08:00–08:30). The result table (variable 'out') lists 5298 distinct (cmdb_id,kpi_name) series present in the window and shows per-series: count_all, count_in_window, anomalies_count (points > global p95), earliest_anomaly_dt, p95_value, max_value_in_window, percent_exceedance, and whether p90 detected anomalies when p95 found none. Top anomalous series include node-level KPIs (node-4, node-1, node-3), service/container KPIs (shippingservice-1, checkoutservice-*), and several mesh-related KPIs from frontend and checkoutservice. To localize the root cause we must aggregate these per component (cmdb_id) to find which components have the most and most severe KPI faults, and their earliest anomaly time. This will narrow candidates for trace/log analysis.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the previously computed per-series table stored in variable 'out', aggregate results to component (cmdb_id) level and return a compact top-20 table. For each cmdb_id compute: series_present = number of distinct kpi_name in window; series_with_anomaly = count of series where anomalies_count>0; total_anomalies = sum of anomalies_count across its series; earliest_anomaly_dt = minimum earliest_anomaly_dt among its series with anomalies (NULL if none); max_percent_exceedance = maximum percent_exceedance among its series; top_kpis_with_anomalies = comma-separated list of up to 5 kpi_name values for which anomalies_count>0 (choose the ones with largest percent_exceedance). Sort the output by series_with_anomaly desc, then total_anomalies desc, then max_percent_exceedance desc. Return the table (limit 20 rows) and the total number of components scanned."
}

{
    "analysis": "We aggregated metric anomalies per component and found many candidates with multiple KPI faults during 2022-03-21 08:00–08:30. Top suspects include checkoutservice-0/1/2, frontend-0/1/2, several adservice pods, node-3, node-4, shippingservice-1, and others. Metrics show both node-level and service/container-level deviations (e.g., large percent_exceedance on node I/O and network KPIs, and many mesh/source KPIs on frontend/checkoutservice). Because multiple service-level components are flagged, the next step is trace analysis to identify the most downstream faulty service or container in the request call chains and to find the earliest failing timestamp. Per rules, we must compute global thresholds on the full trace series before filtering to the incident window, then detect anomalies in the window (look for high latency/error_rate and low traffic/row_count).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using trace.csv, perform the following and return a compact top-20 result table (limit rows to 20):\n1) For each distinct (cmdb_id, trace_name) compute global statistics over the full trace.csv: count_all, min, max, p5, p50, p90, p95. (Do NOT filter by time yet.)\n2) Filter trace.csv to the incident window March 21, 2022 08:00 to 08:30 (Asia/Shanghai). For each (cmdb_id, trace_name) present in the window compute: count_in_window, max_in_window, min_in_window, anomalies_high = number of points with value > global p95, anomalies_low = number of points with value < global p5, earliest_anomaly_dt = smallest timestamp in window where either anomalies_high or anomalies_low occurs.\n3) Return a table of the top 20 (cmdb_id, trace_name) sorted by (anomalies_high+anomalies_low) desc, then by max_in_window desc, showing columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, count_all, count_in_window, anomalies_high, anomalies_low, earliest_anomaly_dt, p95, p5, max_in_window, min_in_window. Also return the total number of distinct (cmdb_id, trace_name) series scanned.\nKeep output compact and bounded. If no anomalies are detected using p95/p5, note that in the result with a boolean flag (no_p95_p5_anomalies)."
}

{
    "analysis": "We computed global thresholds for metrics and detected per-(cmdb_id,kpi_name) anomalies in the incident window (variable 'out' with ~5298 series present). We aggregated anomalies to component level (comp_table_top20) and found many candidates: checkoutservice-0/1/2, frontend-0/1/2, adservice pods, node-3, node-4, shippingservice-1, etc. Trace analysis (trace.csv) shows many trace row_count and to_* row_count series with anomalies, especially frontend.self.row_count and calls from frontend to downstream services, with earliest trace anomalies around 08:00–08:05. Multiple components at both node and service levels show faults, so per the rules we should localize by (1) finding the earliest metric anomaly time across all metric series, (2) listing which component-KPIs first exceeded thresholds at that time (these are candidate root faults), and then (3) use traces/logs to pick the most downstream faulty service/container among those. The next atomic step is therefore to find the absolute earliest anomaly timestamp from the metric anomaly table and enumerate all series that first violated their global p95 at that timestamp (with severity). This will give the first-occurring faults to focus trace/log analysis on.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the per-series anomaly table stored as variable 'out', find the minimum earliest_anomaly_dt across all rows (the earliest anomaly occurrence). Then return a compact table (limit 20 rows) of all rows from 'out' whose earliest_anomaly_dt equals that minimum timestamp. For each matching row include columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, count_all, count_in_window, anomalies_count, earliest_anomaly_dt, p95_value, max_value_in_window, percent_exceedance. Also return a small summary: the minimum earliest_anomaly_dt (as a single value), the number of series that first triggered at that time, and a breakdown of how many of those series are node-level (cmdb_id starting with 'node-') vs pod/service-level (others). Keep output compact and bounded."
}

